2":"1312","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","about 1312":"about 1312","about 1310":"about 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Haughton, Cheshire, England":"Haughton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Bulkeley, Cheshire, England":"Bulkeley, Cheshire, England","Eaton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Eaton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Davenham, Cheshire, England":"Davenham, Cheshire, England","Oteworth, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Butler","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from a word that originally denoted a wine steward, usually the chief servant of a medieval household, from Norman French <i>butuiller</i> (Old French <i>bouteillier</i>, Latin <i>buticularius</i>, from <i>buticula</i> ‘bottle’). In the large households of royalty and the most powerful nobility, the title came to denote an officer of high rank and responsibility, only nominally concerned with the supply of wine, if at all. As well as being widespread in England, this is also the surname of an important Irish family, descended from Theobald FitzWalter, who was appointed Chief Butler of Ireland by King Henry II in 1177. It is Gaelicized as <i>de Buitléir</i>.","English: occasionally perhaps an occupational name from Middle English <i>boteler</i> ‘maker of bottles (usually of leather)’, a derivative of Middle English <i>botel</i>, Old French <i>bo(u)teille</i> ‘bottle’ and synonymous with <i>Botelmaker</i>.","Americanized form of French   Bouthillier   (see   Bouteiller  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Buttler","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Butler  .","German: occupational name for a village tavern owner, from French <i>bouteillier</i> ‘butler’.","Americanized form of German <b>Buttlar</b>: habitational name from a place so named in Thuringia."]},{"name":"Bouthillier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Jacques, Normand, Philippe, Yves.","French: variant of   Bouteiller  . This name is sometimes Americanized as   Butler  . Compare   Boutilier  ."]}]},{"name":"Felice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Roman family name <i>Felix</i> ‘lucky’.  See  <b>Felix</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":10,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":35,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":48,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Felice Butler was born about 1280, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Thomas Butler. She married Robert Bulkeley - Lord of Bulkeley in 1301, in Haughton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died before 1335, in Bulkeley, Cheshire, England."},"et":{"about 1280–before 1335":"umbes 1280–enne 1335","1274–Male":"1274–Surnud","1280–1335":"1280–1335","1269–1313":"1269–1313","1310–1375":"1310–1375","1312–1350":"1312–1350","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","about 1280":"umbes 1280","before 1335":"enne 1335","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1250":"1250","1280":"1280","1290":"1290",